.\" ============================================================================
.\" b76pipe_stream.3 — Willtech Base76 Pipeline Suite Manual
.\" ============================================================================
.Dd April 23, 2026
.Dt B76PIPE_STREAM 3
.Os
.Sh NAME
.Nm b76pipe_stream
.Nd streaming reversible Base76 Stage‑1/Stage‑2 encoder/decoder

.Sh SYNOPSIS
.Nm b76pipe_stream
.Op Fl r
.Op Fl v
.Op Fl i Ar file
.Op Fl o Ar file
.Op Fl -alpha Ar file
.Op Fl -stage1 Op Ar tokens
.Op Fl -selftest Op Ar string
.Op Ar message ...

.Sh DESCRIPTION
The
.Nm
utility implements the canonical Willtech Base76 reversible pipeline as
defined in the Base76 Pipeline Specification (Base76.spec.md).  The pipeline
consists of two deterministic, reversible stages:

.Bl -tag -width Ds
.It Stage‑1
Byte‑to‑Base76 tokenization.  Each byte (0–255) is converted into a Base76
number using the active alphabet.  Tokens are whitespace‑separated.
.It Stage‑2
Bit‑level Base76 encoding.  Each Stage‑1 digit is expanded into 7 bits, and
each bit is encoded as a Base76 digit representing decimal 48 or 49.
.El

The forward pipeline is:

.Bd -literal -offset indent
Bytes → Stage‑1 → Stage‑2
.Ed

The reverse pipeline is:

.Bd -literal -offset indent
Stage‑2 → Stage‑1 → Bytes
.Ed

Both stages are fully reversible and 7‑bit clean.  The program is designed for
streaming environments such as pipes, FIFOs, device files, and long‑running
producers.

.Sh MODES OF OPERATION
.Ss Forward Encoding (default)
Forward mode converts raw bytes into Stage‑1 tokens and then into Stage‑2
Base76 output.  Output is emitted incrementally as input arrives.

If
.Fl v
is specified, Stage‑1 tokens are written to
.Stderr ,
while Stage‑2 output is written to
.Stdout
or to the file specified by
.Fl o .

.Ss Reverse Decoding
Reverse mode reconstructs the bitstream from Stage‑2 Base76 characters,
reassembles Stage‑1 digits, and emits decoded bytes.

Whitespace in the encoded stream is ignored.

.Ss Reverse Decoding of Stage‑1 Tokens
When
.Fl r
is combined with
.Fl -stage1 ,
the program bypasses Stage‑2 entirely and decodes Stage‑1 tokens directly:

.Bd -literal -offset indent
-r --stage1  →  Stage‑1 → bytes
.Ed

This mode is used when Stage‑1 tokens have already been extracted.

.Sh STAGE‑1 FORMAT
Stage‑1 tokens are Base76 numbers encoded using the active alphabet.  Each
token represents a single byte.

Example:
.Bd -literal -offset indent
T  → 18
h  → 1S
i  → 1T
s  → 1d
.Ed

Stage‑1 is used for:
.Bl -bullet -offset indent
.It human‑readable inspection
.It verbose debugging
.It Stage‑1 input mode
.It self‑test diagnostics
.El

.Sh STAGE‑2 FORMAT
Stage‑2 is a 7‑bit clean encoding suitable for restricted channels.

Each Stage‑1 digit is expanded into 7 bits.  Each bit is encoded as:

.Bl -tag -width Ds -offset indent
.It 0
Base76 encoding of decimal 48
.It 1
Base76 encoding of decimal 49
.El

The output is a continuous Base76 stream with no whitespace.

.Sh ALPHABET HANDLING
The Base76 alphabet consists of 76 unique 7‑bit characters.  The default
alphabet is compiled into the binary.

A custom alphabet may be loaded using:
.Pp
.Dl --alpha file
.Pp
The loader applies the following rules:
.Bl -bullet -offset indent
.It only 7‑bit characters (0–127) are considered
.It whitespace is ignored
.It duplicate characters are ignored
.It the first 76 unique characters form the alphabet
.It fewer than 76 unique characters is a fatal error
.El

.Sh SELF‑TEST FACILITY
The
.Fl -selftest
option performs deterministic forward and reverse validation.  Self‑test
always exits after completion.

Supported forms:
.Bl -tag -width Ds
.It Fl -selftest
Use the built‑in diagnostic message.
.It Fl -selftest Ar string
Use the provided string.
.It Fl -selftest Fl i Ar file
Use the contents of
.Ar file .
.It Fl -selftest Fl i Ar file Fl o Ar file
Run the full internal self‑test, then:
.Bl -bullet -offset indent
.It forward‑encode the input file to the output file
.It reverse‑decode the output file
.It compare the decoded data to the original
.El
.El

Self‑test always writes:
.Bl -bullet -offset indent
.It Pa .b76pipe_stream.selftest.i
.It Pa .b76pipe_stream.selftest.o
.El

It is an error to specify both a self‑test string and
.Fl i .

.Sh OPTIONS
.Bl -tag -width Ds
.It Fl i Ar file
Read input from
.Ar file .
.It Fl o Ar file
Write output to
.Ar file .
.It Fl r
Reverse (decode) mode.
.It Fl v
Verbose mode.  Print Stage‑1 tokens to
.Stderr .
.It Fl - -stage1 Op Ar tokens
Interpret input as Stage‑1 tokens.  In reverse mode, decode Stage‑1 directly.
.It Fl - -alpha Ar file
Load a custom Base76 alphabet.
.It Fl - -selftest Op Ar string
Run internal forward/reverse validation and exit.
.It Fl h , Fl - -help
Display usage information.
.It Fl - -version
Display program version.
.El

.Sh STREAMING BEHAVIOUR
.Nm
does not buffer the entire input and is safe for use with:
.Bl -bullet -offset indent
.It pipes
.It FIFOs
.It device files
.It long‑running producers
.El

Output is emitted as soon as enough data is available to produce the next
token or byte.

.Sh EXIT STATUS
.Bl -tag -width Ds
.It 0
Success.
.It 1
Error in input, alphabet, self‑test, or pipeline operation.
.El

.Sh FILES
.Bl -tag -width Ds
.It Pa .b76pipe_stream.selftest.i
Self‑test input file.
.It Pa .b76pipe_stream.selftest.o
Self‑test encoded output file.
.El

.Sh EXAMPLES
Encode a file:
.Bd -literal -offset indent
$ b76pipe_stream -i message.bin -o message.b76
.Ed

Decode a Base76 file:
.Bd -literal -offset indent
$ b76pipe_stream -r -i message.b76 -o message.bin
.Ed

Verbose Stage‑1 output:
.Bd -literal -offset indent
$ b76pipe_stream -v -i input.bin
.Ed

Decode Stage‑1 tokens directly:
.Bd -literal -offset indent
$ b76pipe_stream -r --stage1 "18 1S 1T 1d"
.Ed

Run self‑test with custom input:
.Bd -literal -offset indent
$ b76pipe_stream --selftest "Hello Base76"
.Ed

Run full file‑based self‑test:
.Bd -literal -offset indent
$ b76pipe_stream --selftest -i data.bin -o encoded.txt
.Ed

